If the server responds with a 206 Partial Content status code
(which we don't handle),
the response must not be cached regardless of other Cache-Control response directives.

-- cache.txt --
GET http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=604800
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

Hello, World!
GET http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=604800
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

Hello, World!
-- server.txt --
GET http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=604800
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

Hello, World!
GET http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

HTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=604800
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

Hello, World!
